<div class="container my-5">
  <!-- Article Header -->
  <div class="row mb-4">
    <div class="col text-center">
      <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold">How Much Money Will You Really Make in Investment Banking?</h1>
      <p class="text-muted">December 10, 2024</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-lg-8 mx-auto">
      <p class="lead">
        There are plenty of reasons you’ll rattle off in your investment banking interviews about why you want to enter the industry. Maybe you’re "fascinated by financial markets," "excited about the opportunity to work with CEOs," or "eager to support shareholder value." Some of these reasons might even be true.
      </p>
      <p class="lead">
        But let’s be honest—for the vast majority of people entering the field, the main driver is the money. That, and the hope of pivoting into private equity. Yet the question remains: <strong>how much money will you actually make?</strong> And what does that mean for your life?
      </p>
      <p class="lead">
        Will you be driving Lambos and flying private jets by 30? Probably not. But if you have some discipline and grind it out for a few years, you’ll likely achieve something much rarer: <strong>financial freedom.</strong> Here’s what that could realistically look like, depending on your career path.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

