  <!-- Accordion: Investment Banking Career Paths -->
  <div class="accordion mt-5" id="bankingPathsAccordion">
    <h2 class="fw-bold">Investment Banking Career Paths</h2>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingOne">
        <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseOne" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseOne">
          Example 1: Analyst → Private Equity → Business School
        </button>
      </h2>
      <div id="collapseOne" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingOne" data-bs-parent="#bankingPathsAccordion">
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <p>This is the classic path. After two grueling years as an investment banking analyst, you jump into private equity, spend a few years there, and then go back to business school (or just continue in PE).</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Years 1–2:</strong> $180k/year; save $60k/year.</li>
            <li><strong>Years 3–5:</strong> $300k/year in PE; save $120k/year.</li>
            <li><strong>Years 6–7:</strong> B-school costs $210k, net worth: $0–$50k by age 27.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwo">
        <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwo">
          Example 2: Analyst → Stay in Banking Through VP
        </button>
      </h2>
      <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwo" data-bs-parent="#bankingPathsAccordion">
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <p>Another common path is sticking with investment banking and climbing the ladder to VP. This requires grinding for at least six years (Analyst → Associate → VP), and the money ramps up quickly.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Years 1–3:</strong> $180k/year; save $60k/year.</li>
            <li><strong>Years 4–6:</strong> $350k/year as Associate; save $150k/year.</li>
            <li><strong>Year 7:</strong> $700k/year as VP; save $300k/year.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
        <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
          Example 3: MBA Associate with Debt and a Family
        </button>
      </h2>
      <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree" data-bs-parent="#bankingPathsAccordion">
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <p>If you enter banking as an MBA graduate with debt and a family, your financial trajectory changes significantly due to debt payments and family expenses.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Year 1:</strong> $350k/year; save $50k–$70k/year.</li>
            <li><strong>Years 2–4:</strong> $400k/year; save $100k/year.</li>
            <li><strong>Net Worth by Age 30:</strong> $200k–$300k.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFour">
        <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFour" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFour">
          Example 4: MBA Associate Without Debt
        </button>
      </h2>
      <div id="collapseFour" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFour" data-bs-parent="#bankingPathsAccordion">
        <div class="accordion-body">
          <p>If you’re an MBA Associate without debt or family obligations, your financial growth is much faster, resembling the Analyst → VP path.</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Years 1–3:</strong> $350k/year; save $150k/year.</li>
            <li><strong>Years 4–6:</strong> $700k/year as VP; save $300k/year.</li>
            <li><strong>Net Worth by Age 30:</strong> $1M–$1.3M.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Section: Comparing to Other Career Paths -->
  <div class="row mt-5">
    <div class="col-lg-8 mx-auto">
      <h2 class="fw-bold">How Does This Compare to Other Career Paths?</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Ok, that’s great and all, but how does this compare to other career paths? And with the stat that <strong>less than 1% of college graduates</strong> break into investment banking and <strong>top MBA programs placing only around 15%</strong> of their graduating classes into the field, if you can get into this competitive industry, you likely could enter other prestigious fields as well.
      </p>
      <p class="lead">
        What really matters is how investment banking stacks up against other <strong>high-paying, competitive career paths</strong>. Let’s go through a few common ones and weigh the pros and cons for different personality types, along with how the financial outcomes compare.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

    <!-- Accordion: Other Career Paths -->
    <div class="accordion mt-4" id="otherPathsAccordion">
      <!-- Consulting -->
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingConsulting">
          <button class="accordion-button" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseConsulting" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseConsulting">
            Consulting
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseConsulting" class="accordion-collapse collapse show" aria-labelledby="headingConsulting" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Most similar to banking in terms of skills and applicant base.</li>
              <li>Better work-life balance and greater industry flexibility.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Slower financial growth, with lower starting salaries.</li>
              <li>Fewer opportunities to become a multi-millionaire.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Net Worth Difference:</strong> $500k–$700k at age 30 vs. $1M+ for bankers.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
  
      <!-- Lawyer -->
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingLawyer">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseLawyer" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseLawyer">
            Lawyer
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseLawyer" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingLawyer" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>High salaries at big law firms ($190k+ starting out after law school).</li>
              <li>Structured career path with clear milestones.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Longer and more expensive schooling than banking.</li>
              <li>Slower financial payoff, with partnerships taking 8–10 years.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Net Worth Difference:</strong> $300k–$500k by age 30, compared to $1M+ for bankers.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
  
      <!-- Doctor -->
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingDoctor">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseDoctor" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseDoctor">
            Doctor
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseDoctor" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingDoctor" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>High societal respect and meaningful work directly helping people.</li>
              <li>Long-term earnings potential for specialists is excellent.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Lengthy training path (medical school + residency + fellowship).</li>
              <li>Financial payoff comes late—mid-30s or later for significant earnings.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Net Worth Difference:</strong> Doctors often start with net debt by 30, compared to bankers with $1M+.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
  
      <!-- Software Engineer -->
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingEngineer">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseEngineer" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseEngineer">
            Software Engineer
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseEngineer" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingEngineer" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Great starting pay ($120k–$180k at top companies).</li>
              <li>Flexible hours and better work-life balance than banking.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Career progression plateaus for many engineers in non-management roles.</li>
              <li>Stock-based compensation is volatile and market-dependent.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Net Worth Difference:</strong> $700k–$1M by age 30, comparable to banking associates but behind VPs.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
  
      <!-- Directly to the Buyside -->
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingBuyside">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseBuyside" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseBuyside">
            Going Directly to the Buyside
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseBuyside" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingBuyside" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Higher starting pay than banking ($300k–$500k at top firms).</li>
              <li>Better work-life balance compared to banking.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>As competitive as banking, often harder to break in without prior banking experience.</li>
              <li>Strong finance knowledge required to excel.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Net Worth Difference:</strong> $1M+ by age 30, similar to bankers.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
  
      <!-- Corporate Role -->
      <div class="accordion-item">
        <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingCorporate">
          <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseCorporate" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseCorporate">
            Corporate Role
          </button>
        </h2>
        <div id="collapseCorporate" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingCorporate" data-bs-parent="#otherPathsAccordion">
          <div class="accordion-body">
            <p><strong>Pros:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Stable hours and predictable workload—ideal for work-life balance.</li>
              <li>Easier to break into directly after school.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Cons:</strong></p>
            <ul>
              <li>Slower financial growth, with fewer paths to high-income roles.</li>
              <li>Starting pay is significantly lower ($50k–$80k/year).</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Net Worth Difference:</strong> $200k–$400k by age 30, far behind bankers.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  



 <!-- Conclusion -->
 <div class="row mt-5">
  <div class="col-lg-8 mx-auto">
    <h2 class="fw-bold">Conclusion: The Cost of Financial Freedom</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      Investment banking is fascinating, fast-paced, and gives you a front-row seat to billion-dollar deals. It’s an industry where you feel important, constantly challenged, and always surrounded by ambition.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      But let’s not sugarcoat it: the job is <strong>incredibly mentally and physically taxing.</strong> The hours are brutal, the demands never stop, and your personal life will take a backseat.
    </p>
    <p class="lead">
      However, the payoff is something rare—financial freedom early in life. With discipline and focus, banking gives you the opportunity to accumulate wealth at a pace most careers can’t match. Sacrifice now, and for the right kind of person, it can pay dividends down the road.
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
